docs.abstract: Large technology companies, and the big profits they produce, lifted the markets earlier this year. But during October’s tumble they were only part of a broad-based downturn.
docs.snippet: Large technology companies, and the big profits they produce, lifted the markets earlier this year. But during October’s tumble they were only part of a broad-based downturn.
docs.lead_paragraph: The world’s largest technology companies drove the stock market to record highs earlier this year. As stocks have tumbled, though, it’s more like they’re just along for the ride.

headline.main: Tech Drove Stocks Skyward. It Was a Different Story on the Way Down.
headline.print_headline: Market Soared On Tech’s Back, Then It Soured All on Its Own

docs.abstract: The new anthology from the creator of “Mad Men” has moments of wonder amid sluggish storytelling.
docs.snippet: The new anthology from the creator of “Mad Men” has moments of wonder amid sluggish storytelling.
docs.lead_paragraph: As the creator of “Mad Men,” Matthew Weiner had a thing about spoilers. Each season arrived with a list of no-nos for critics, such as the number of floors in the advertising office where it was set. When he announced a series for Amazon Prime, I joked that maybe he’d make it a spoiler to say what the new show was about.

headline.main: Review: ‘The Romanoffs’ Is Elegant but Frustrating
headline.print_headline: All in the Family: Eclectic, but Frustrating

docs.abstract: Many in the tech industry don’t want to be part of the military-industrial complex. But defense work is already part of Silicon Valley’s DNA.
docs.snippet: Many in the tech industry don’t want to be part of the military-industrial complex. But defense work is already part of Silicon Valley’s DNA.
docs.lead_paragraph: The sunny precincts of Silicon Valley have been wrestling for months with the question of whether technology companies should stay out of work related to the military. Google recently announced that it would no longer compete for a $10 billion Pentagon cloud computing contract. Microsoft employees have pressured its chief executive to do the same.

headline.main: Silicon Valley Can’t Escape the Business of War

docs.abstract: Profit-sharing plans for rank-and-file employees are vanishing as corporate America has adopted a new approach toward who reaps a healthy company’s gains.
docs.snippet: Profit-sharing plans for rank-and-file employees are vanishing as corporate America has adopted a new approach toward who reaps a healthy company’s gains.
docs.lead_paragraph: Half a century ago, a typical Sears salesman could walk out of the store at retirement with a nest egg worth well over a million in today’s dollars, feathered with company stock. A warehouse worker hired now at Amazon who stays until retirement would leave with a fraction of that.

headline.main: When Sears Flourished, So Did Workers. At Amazon, It’s More Complicated.
headline.print_headline: In Its Heyday, Sears Spread the Wealth. Companies Today Don’t.
